Jason W Solinsky (solman@athena.mit.edu) wrote:

: In article <tph-2907940033240001@slip873.rmii.com>, tph@rmii.com (Tom Harrington) writes:

: |> So what you're saying is that, if someone in Europe were to download
: |> a copy of nCrypt, the US government would try to get the *author* of
: |> the program sent to prison???  The federal government never ceases to
: |> amaze me.  It would seem that, if warnings were in place, that the
: |> downloader would be the "guilty" party for having transported the
: |> program outside the US.

: Well first of all, I don't believe that the government would even dream of
: prosecuting somebody for distributing cryptography over the net. I intend
: to test this soon if I am not beaten to it. Any attempt at prosecution would
: provide enough negative publicity to sink any Gorewelian cryptographic
: policy that might be in the making.

: Second of all, they would not try to prosecute those who made the program,
: only those who distributed it. If the program gets into foreign hands,
: SOMEBODY has to have given it to them. Potential subjects for prosecution
: include the person who uploaded it, the person who runs the site to which
: it was uploaded, and the person who runs the last US site that the program
: goes through. Once upon a time BITNET was told that all US sites are
: responsible for any cryptography that goes through them. As you can see its
: a silly law, like Massachusetts blue laws. The government doesn't have the
: guts to arest anybody here for blasphemy and the government doesn't have
: the guts to arrest anybody for distributing cryptography over the net.
: Both would violate the bill of rights and both would result in enourmous
: amounts of bad publicity.

Then why is Paul Zimmerman in jail?

